<solution><statement><ol><li>Recall that 

<me>
f_x(x,y) = \lim_{h \to 0} \frac{f(x+h,y) - f(x,y)}{h},
</me>
 
which gives us the slope of the tangent line to the trace in the <m>x</m> direction. We can approximate this slope with the slope of a secant line, choosing points equally spaced on both sides of <m>(x,y)</m>. In other words,

<me>
f_x(x,y) \approx \frac{f(x+h,y) - f(x-h,y)}{2h},
</me>
 
for small values of <m>h</m>. This is the symmetric difference quotient from calculus 1. 
Using <m>h=1</m> and approximating values from the contour plot gives us  

<me>
f_x(-2, -1) \approx \frac{f(-1,-1)-f(-3,-1)}{2} \approx \frac{4.5-2.9}{2} = 0.8.
</me>
</li>
<li>We approximate <m>f_y(-2,-1)</m> in the same way, using <m>h=1</m> again. So 

<me>
f_y(-2,-1) \approx \frac{f(-2,0)-f(-2,-2)}{2} \approx \frac{2.4-6}{2} = -1.8.
</me>
</li>
<li>As above, 

<md><mrow>f_x(-1,2) \amp \approx \frac{f(0,2)-f(-2,2)}{2} \approx \frac{3-0.8}{2} = 1.1</mrow>
 <mrow>f_y(-1,2) \amp \approx \frac{f(-1,3)-f(-1,1)}{2} \approx \frac{2.1-2.3}{2} = -0.1.</mrow>
 
</md>
</li>
<li>A point at which <m>f_x(x,y) = 0</m> will occur when we have a horizontal tangent line. Such a point occurs near <m>(0,-0.5)</m>.</li>
<li>A point at which <m>f_y(x,y) = 0</m> will occur when we have a vertical tangent line. Such a point occurs near <m>(-1,2)</m>.</li>
<li>We want a point at which <m>f</m> is decreasing in the <m>x</m>-direction. Such a point is <m>(2,-2)</m>.</li>
<li>We want a point at which <m>f</m> is increasing in the <m>y</m>-direction. Such a point is <m>(-1.2,-1)</m>.</li>
<li>A possible plot is shown at left below.</li>
<li>A possible plot is shown at right below.
